","1090":"1090","1020":"1020","1064":"1064","1073":"1073","1040":"1040","1082":"1082","from about 1073 to 1082":"fra omkring 1073 til 1082","1127":"1127","1015":"1015","1034":"1034","about 1064":"omkring 1064","about 1034":"omkring 1034","Torres,Sardinia,Italy.":"Sardegna, Italien","Logudoro, Sardinia, Italy":"Logudoro, Sardegna, Italien","Oristano, Sardinia, Italy":"Oristano, Sardegna, Italien"},"nl":{"about 1034–about 1082":"circa 1034–circa 1082","1034–1082":"1034–1082","1040–1090":"1040–1090","1064–1127":"1064–1127","1020–1073":"1020–1073","1015–Female":"1015–Overleden","about 1082":"circa 1082","1090":"1090","1020":"1020","1064":"1064","1073":"1073","1040":"1040","1082":"1082","from about 1073 to 1082":"van circa 1073 to 1082","1127":"1127","1015":"1015","1034":"1034","about 1064":"circa 1064","about 1034":"circa 1034","Torres,Sardinia,Italy.":"Sardegna, Italië","Logudoro, Sardinia, Italy":"Logudoro, Sardegna, Italië","Oristano, Sardinia, Italy":"Oristano, Sardegna, Italië"},"en":{"about 1034–about 1082":"about 1034–about 1082","1034–1082":"1034–1082","1040–1090":"1040–1090","1064–1127":"1064–1127","1020–1073":"1020–1073","1015–Female":"1015–Deceased","about 1082":"about 1082","1090":"1090","1020":"1020","1064":"1064","1073":"1073","1040":"1040","1082":"1082","from about 1073 to 1082":"from about 1073 to 1082","1127":"1127","1015":"1015","1034":"1034","about 1064":"about 1064","about 1034":"about 1034","Torres,Sardinia,Italy.":"Sardinia, Italy","Logudoro, Sardinia, Italy":"Logudoro, Sardinia, Italy","Oristano, Sardinia, Italy":"Oristano, Sardinia, Italy","nameMeanings":[{"name":"di","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Chinese:","Mandarin form of the surname 狄, a term referring to the tribes in ancient northern China: (i) from Di (狄), the name of an ancient state (thought to have been located in Hebei or Shandong province), which was granted to Xiao Bo or Kao Bo by King Cheng of Zhou (reigned 1042–1021  BC ). (ii) adopted as a surname by the Ku Di (庫狄) family during the Northern Wei dynasty (386–534  AD ). (iii) traced back to other minority ethnic groups in ancient northwestern China.","Mandarin form of the Chinese surname 邸, meaning ‘official residence’ in Chinese: (i) from placename Di (邸), the name of a county (unidentified location). (ii) said to be borne by some descendants of Kujula Kadphises (called 丘就郤 or 邸就郤 in Chinese, 30–<i>c.</i> 80  AD ), founder of the Kushan Empire (one branch of the Yuezhi people originating from western China) located in Central Asia during the Eastern Han dynasty (25–220  AD )."],"variants":[{"name":"Chi","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese Young, Dong, Yun, Cheng, Jae, Yong, Cheng Chung, Chi, Chun, Duk, Fang, Feng.  Korean Chung, Chong, Jae Hong, Moon, Myong, Pong, Shen, Yoo, Byung, Chang, Chol, Chong Hun.  Southeast Asian Phi, Hung, Ly, Tu, Denh, Do Van, Duong, Hao, Kieu, Mui, Nga, Phat.","Chinese: Mandarin and Cantonese form of the surname 池, meaning ‘moat’ in ancient Chinese: (i) acquired as a surname by people who lived beside a moat. (ii) from Chi (池), said to be the name of an ancient state (of unknown location and period). (iii) from the personal name Chi (池), personal name of a son of an official in the state of Qin during the Spring and Autumn period (770–476  BC ).","Chinese: Mandarin and Cantonese form of the surname 遲, meaning ‘late’ in Chinese: (i) borne by descendants of Chi Ren (遲任), a person who lived during the Shang dynasty (1600–1046  BC ). (ii) shortened form of the Chinese compound surname Yu-Chi (尉遲), originally the name of a tribe from the Xianbei ethnic group in northern China. (iii) from the second element of the personal name Zi Chi (子遲), style name of Fan Xu, a student of Confucius (551–479  BC )."]}]},{"name":"Lacon","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["1  English: locative name from Lacon in Wem (Shrops). This name has probably been confused with or absorbed by   Lakin   (1), especially in counties adjoining Shrops, such as Staffs.","2  English: while the name in Yorks could be that in (1) through migration, its appearance in late 14th-century Clint in the north-west of WR Yorks, and the persistent final  <i>-can</i> in most early forms of the surname, suggest that it may have had a different but unknown origin."],"variants":[{"name":"Laken","meanings":["1  English:  see  Lakin  .","2  English:  see  Lacon  ."]},{"name":"Laking","meanings":["English:  see  Lacon   and   Lakin  ."]},{"name":"Lakin","meanings":["Americanized form of Jewish <i>Leykin</i> (from Belarus), a metronymic from <i>Leyke</i>, a pet form of the Yiddish female personal name <i>Leye</i>, from the Hebrew female personal name <i>Lea</i>, from which English <i>Leah</i> is derived (see Genesis 29: 16) + the Slavic possessive suffix <i>-in</i>.","English: patronymic from the Middle English personal name <i>Lawkin</i>, a diminutive of <i>Law-</i> (a pet form of the personal name <i>Laurence</i>; see   Lawrence  ). Compare   Law   1 and   Larkin  ."]}]},{"name":"Gunale,","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["German: from a variant of   Gundel  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Gundel","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Hans.","South German (also <b>Gündel</b>): from a short form of any of various ancient Germanic personal names beginning with <i>gund</i> ‘battle’."]}]},{"name":"Mariano","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Carlos, Pablo, Alfonso, Ernesto, Fernando, Gregorio, Jesus, Luz, Manuel, Marcelo, Rolando.  Italian Antonio, Angelo, Rocco, Vito, Nicola, Fausto, Federico, Mabini, Romeo, Alessandra, Arcangelo, Caesar.","Italian and Spanish: from the personal name <i>Mariano</i>, from the Latin surname <i>Marianus</i> (a derivative of the old personal name <i>Marius</i>, of Etruscan origin). In the early Christian era it came to be taken as an adjective derived from <i>Maria</i>, and was associated with the cult of the Virgin Mary. It was borne by various early Christian saints, including a 3rd-century martyr in Numibia and a 5th-century hermit of Berry, France."],"variants":[{"name":"Marjanovic","meanings":["Serbian and Croatian (<b>Marjanović</b>): patronymic from the personal name <i>Marjan</i>, Latin <i>Marianus</i> (see   Mariano  )."]},{"name":"Mariana","meanings":["Extended spelling of   Marian  , reinforcing the association of the second element with   Ann(e) .  It also represents a French assimilated form of   Mariamne .  <i>Marianne</i> is the name used for the symbolic figure of the French Republic."]},{"name":"Marian","meanings":["Originally a medieval variant spelling of   Marion .  However, in the 18th century, when combined names began to come into fashion, it was sometimes understood as a combination of   Mary   and   Ann ."]},{"name":"Mariani","meanings":["Originally a medieval variant spelling of   Marion .  However, in the 18th century, when combined names began to come into fashion, it was sometimes understood as a combination of   Mary   and   Ann ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Mariano I di Lacon Gunale, Judge of Torres was born about 1034, in Sardinia, Italy, his father, Andrea Tanca di Lacon-Gunale, Judge of Torres, was 16 and his mother, Preziosa de Orrubu, was 21. He had at least 1 son with Susanna de Zori. He died about 1082, in Logudoro, Sardinia, Italy, at the age of 50."},"et":{"about 1034–about 1082":"umbes 1034–umbes 1082","1034–1082":"1034–1082","1040–1090":"1040–1090","1064–1127":"1064–1127","1020–1073":"1020–1073","1015–Female":"1015–Surnud","about 1082":"umbes 1082","1090":"1090","1020":"1020","1064":"1064","1073":"1073","1040":"1040","1082":"1082","from about 1073 to 1082":"umbes 1073 kuni 1082","1127":"1127","1